🚨 Pre-Flight Warning
Because we are stepping up to exam-level logic, you must do this on your RHEL 9 VM. RHEL 10 handles some of these underlying mechanics differently, and practicing on it now might betray your muscle memory on test day.

📝 RHCSA Mock Exam Level 2: "The Logic Puzzle"
Time Limit: 90 Minutes.
Goal: Accuracy, verification, and using the man pages when you forget a flag.

Task 1: The Non-Standard User
The security team needs a service account for a legacy application.

Create a group named legacy_app with a specific GID of 3050.

Create a user named app_runner.

The user app_runner must belong to the legacy_app group as its primary group.

The user must have a custom home directory located at /opt/app_runner (not /home/app_runner).

The user must not be able to log in to an interactive shell.

Task 2: The "Safe" Collaboration Directory
Your development team needs a shared workspace, but they keep accidentally deleting each other's files.

Create a directory at /mnt/dev_share.

Change the group ownership to the legacy_app group.

Ensure anyone in the legacy_app group can read, write, and execute in this directory.

The Catch: You must configure the directory so that users can only delete or rename files that they personally created. (They cannot delete another user's file).

Task 3: The Surgical Search
Your server is running out of inodes, and you need to find old, small config files.

Find all files inside the /etc directory that end with the .conf extension and are smaller than 10KB.

Copy (do not move) all the files you find into a new directory located at /root/conf_backups.

Hint: You must do this in a single command pipeline using find.

Task 4: The Precision Sudo
The app_runner user (from Task 1) needs to be able to restart the firewalld service, but nothing else.

Configure the system so that app_runner can run systemctl restart firewalld with root privileges.

They must NOT be prompted for a password when they run it.

Constraint: Do not edit the main /etc/sudoers file directly. Use a drop-in file.

Task 5: The Silent Cron Job
You need a heartbeat monitor that logs the system uptime, but you don't want it spamming your local mail spool with errors.

Schedule a cron job for the root user to run every 5 minutes.

The job should run the uptime command and append the output to /var/log/system_heartbeat.log.

The Catch: You must redirect all Standard Error (stderr) to /dev/null so that if the command fails, it fails silently.

Task 6: The Ghost Link
A script is hardcoded to look for a file at /tmp/database_config.yaml, but the actual file lives at /etc/app/config.yaml.

Create the necessary directory and the actual file at /etc/app/config.yaml. Write "version: 1.0" inside it.

Create a link at /tmp/database_config.yaml that points to the actual file.

The Catch: It must be a link that survives even if the /tmp directory is moved to a different filesystem partition. (Think about the difference between Hard Links and Soft Links).

Task 7: Time Travel
The server was provisioned in the wrong physical datacenter zone.

Change the system's timezone to UTC.

Verify that the NTP service (chronyd) is currently active and synchronizing the clock.

🛑 Evaluation Phase (The Answer Key)
Do not look at this until you have attempted all 7 tasks! Try to use man find, man chmod, etc., to figure out the syntax before peeking.

Task 1: The Non-Standard User (15 Points)

Bash

sudo groupadd -g 3050 legacy_app
sudo useradd -g legacy_app -d /opt/app_runner -s /sbin/nologin app_runner
(Logic: -g forces primary group, -G would be secondary. -d specifies the home dir. -s sets the shell).

Task 2: The "Safe" Collaboration Directory (15 Points)

Bash

sudo mkdir -p /mnt/dev_share
sudo chgrp legacy_app /mnt/dev_share
sudo chmod 2770 /mnt/dev_share  # Adds SGID (2) so files inherit the group
sudo chmod +t /mnt/dev_share    # Adds the Sticky Bit (+t) so users can only delete their own files
# Alternatively, in one command: sudo chmod 3770 /mnt/dev_share
Task 3: The Surgical Search (20 Points)

Bash

sudo mkdir /root/conf_backups
sudo find /etc -type f -name "*.conf" -size -10k -exec cp {} /root/conf_backups/ \;
(Logic: -size -10k means less than 10KB. -exec runs a command on the results, {} represents the file found, and \; closes the exec loop).

Task 4: The Precision Sudo (15 Points)

Bash

sudo visudo -f /etc/sudoers.d/app_runner
# Add this exact line:
app_runner ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart firewalld
Task 5: The Silent Cron Job (15 Points)

Bash

sudo crontab -e
# Add this exact line:
*/5 * * * * /usr/bin/uptime >> /var/log/system_heartbeat.log 2> /dev/null
(Logic: */5 means every 5 minutes. >> appends standard output. 2> redirects standard error).

Task 6: The Ghost Link (10 Points)

Bash

sudo mkdir -p /etc/app
echo "version: 1.0" | sudo tee /etc/app/config.yaml
sudo ln -s /etc/app/config.yaml /tmp/database_config.yaml
(Logic: Hard links cannot cross filesystem boundaries. /tmp and /etc are often on different partitions. Therefore, you must use a Soft Link -s).

Task 7: Time Travel (10 Points)

Bash

sudo timedatectl set-timezone UTC
sudo systemctl status chronyd
Fire up that RHEL 9 VM and give this a shot.
